.TH "HTMLTEMPLATEELEMENT.CONTENT" "3JS" "December 1, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
HTMLTemplateElement.content \- HTMLTemplateElement: content property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]content\f[B]\f[R] property of the
\f[CR]HTMLTemplateElement\f[R] interface returns the
\f[CR]<template>\f[R] element\(cqs template contents as a
\f[CR]DocumentFragment\f[R].
This content\(cqs \f[CR]ownerDocument\f[R] is a separate
\f[CR]Document\f[R] from the one that contains the \f[CR]<template>\f[R]
element itself \(em unless the containing document is itself constructed
for the purpose of holding template content.
.PP
The \f[CR]Node.cloneNode()\f[R] and \f[CR]Document.importNode()\f[R]
methods both create a copy of a node.
The difference is that \f[CR]importNode()\f[R] clones the node in the
context of the calling document, whereas \f[CR]cloneNode()\f[R] uses the
document of the node being cloned.
The document context determines the \f[CR]CustomElementRegistry\f[R] for
constructing any custom elements.
For this reason, use \f[CR]document.importNode()\f[R] to clone the
\f[CR]content\f[R] fragment so that custom element descendants are
constructed using the definitions in the current document, rather than
the separate document that owns the template content.
See the \f[CR]Node.cloneNode()\f[R] page\(cqs examples for more details.
.SH VALUE
A \f[CR]DocumentFragment\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using importNode() with template content
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] templateElement = document.querySelector(\(dq#foo\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] documentFragment = document.importNode(templateElement.content, \f[B]true\f[R]);
\f[I]// Now you can insert the documentFragment into the DOM\f[R]
.EE
.SS The ownerDocument of template content
For \f[CR]<template>\f[R] elements created in the context of a normal
HTML document, the \f[CR]ownerDocument\f[R] of the \f[CR]content\f[R] is
a separate, freshly created document:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] template = document.createElement(\(dqtemplate\(dq);
console.log(template.content.ownerDocument === document); \f[I]// false\f[R]
console.log(template.content.ownerDocument.URL); \f[I]// \(dqabout:blank\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.PP
If the \f[CR]<template>\f[R] element is created in the context of a
document that itself was created for the purpose of holding template
content, then the \f[CR]ownerDocument\f[R] of the \f[CR]content\f[R] is
the same as that of the containing document:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] template1 = document.createElement(\(dqtemplate\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] docForTemplate = template1.content.ownerDocument;
\f[B]const\f[R] template2 = docForTemplate.createElement(\(dqtemplate\(dq);
console.log(template2.content.ownerDocument === docForTemplate); \f[I]// true\f[R]
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]HTMLTemplateElement\f[R]
